featured_reviews.review_translated_text:
"Hill Jatra"
Hiljatra festival of Soroghati of Pithoragarh - is mainly a festival of farmers and cattle herders which is considered to be a gift of Nepal.
* Hilayatra is made up of two words 'Hil' and 'Jatra'. Hill means a bordered (marshy) place and Jatra means game or journey, i.e. the game performed in a marshy place is Hill Yatra. Hilaytra is organized only in rainy season. When the fields are filled with water and paddy has been planted.
* This is a special theater style of Uttarakhand in which different characters act wearing big wooden masks. In this, there are characters like horseman, soldier, sweeper, machera, dahiwala, haliya, pair of bulls, girls planting paddy, deer, chital, Nepalese king, dog, bear, barber, bhajan group, lachiya ghost etc. * It was organized in villages like Kumour, Bajti, Bhurbhudi, Melda, Khatigaon, Balakot, Sil, Chamu, Aganya etc. of Pithoragarh.

The Pithoragarh Fort, also known as the London Fort, is a popular tourist destination. Although the fort is small in size, it offers a pleasant experience. The entry ticket is priced at INR 20 per person, and car and bike parking passes are available at an additional cost of INR 50 for car parking.

Inside the fort, there are several shops where visitors can explore and purchase local items. Additionally, there is a museum that showcases the history and culture of the region. One of the notable features of the fort is a pipal tree, which adds to the serene atmosphere. The surroundings are well-maintained and clean.

While the fort may not be as large or grand as some other forts, it still provides a glimpse into the history of the area and offers a tranquil setting. Visitors can enjoy exploring the fort and its surroundings, making it a worthwhile visit for those interested in historical sites and cultural experiences.

featured_reviews.review_id:
Pithoragarh Fort (Hindi: pithauraagddh' kilaa) is a fort in Pithoragarh in the Indian state of Uttarakhand. It was built during Chand period by regional ruler Peeru Alias Prithwi Gusain. According to some records, this fort was constructed by the Gorkhas in the year 1789, after invading the town. The Pithoragarh Fort is situated on a hill on the outskirts of the town of Pithoragarh. At present, the fort is in dilapidated condition.

Pithoragarh Fort, also known by many other names like the London Fort, Baulaki Fort (bowl-shaped fort), and the Gorkha Killa is among the top places to visit in the Pithoragarh District of Uttarakhand. This small fort gives a majestic top view of Pithoragarh nestled in the Kali Kumaon Hills.

So, let us explore this tiny but beautiful fort...

Pithoragarh Fort is located in the easternmost district of Uttarakhand state, Pithoragarh, also famous by the name of Mini Kashmir of Uttarakhand.

It is situated at an approximate altitude of 1650 meters from the sea level, as written on the plaque outside the fort.

Distance of Pithoragarh from main cities of India is given here- Delhi-496 km, Mumbai-1885 km, Chennai-2356 km, Kolkata-1423 km, Haridwar-436 km, Dehradun-489 km, Jaipur-736 km, Shimla-803 km, Lucknow-441 km Ahmedabad-1409 km and Bengaluru-2363 km.
The fort is said to be constructed by Peeru Alias Prithvi Gusain, who ruled the region in the Chand Period, in the year 1789.

The town was ruled by the Chand dynasty and got its name Pthoragarh from the ruler Pithora Chand. Also, the fort was named as Pithoragarh Fort after the name of the town Pithoragarh.

In 1815, the area of Kumaon was captured by the Britishers and they changed the fort's name from Baulaki Fort to London fort under the leadership of E.Gardner.

For more than 130 years, since 1881, this fort was used as a working office for tehsil, but now it is being converted to its original form to attract tourists.

Efforts are continuously made to save this fort from getting ruined and adding new features like museum to it for promoting tourism and declaring as a National Heritage.

It is spread over an area of about 6.5 Nali or 1300 sq. meters. Nali is a unit to measure area of land and is mainly used in Uttarakhand. 1 nali (drain land) =200.6 sq. m.

It mainly contains open grounds, with around 6-7 feet high walls, meant to be safe from attacks of enemies. The length of the walls is about 88.5 meters.

The thick walls also have 152 holes for firing guns on the enemies without being get noticed by them.

A memorial plaque is also located inside the fort that states that 1005 soldiers participated in the World War I from Pithoragarh and 32 of them lost their lives.

Many rooms with tilted maroon roofs, are also present within the fort premises to house museum and art collections in them.
The nearest Railway Station to the Pithoragarh Fort is the Tanakpur Railway Station, which is located at a distance of 148 km from the fort. Cars and taxi services can be used to reach the fort.

The nearest Airport to the Pithoragarh Fort is the Naini Saini Airport, at a driving distance of 7 km and can be accessed within 20 minutes.

Pithoragarh district is well connected with the other parts of the state through roads also. Buses are the best mode of transport from nearby areas in Uttarakhand.

Entry Fee-
The entry fee charged to the visitors is INR 10 per person and that seems to be optimum with the less management and development works done there.

No entry fee is charged to children below the age of 5 years.

Timings of the fort-
The timings of this fort are from 11:00 am to 7:00 pm. And it is open for the visitors on all the days of a week.

Hotels and Restaurants Nearby-
Kumaon Mandal Vikas Nigam guest houses and hotels are the best accommodation that one can have in the close vicinity of the Pithoragarh Fort.

Saraswati Restaurant, Meghna, and Jyonar are some of the places to eat nearby the fort. A canteen is also located within the fort premises.

featured_reviews.review_id:
Perched majestically on a hill on the outskirts of the town of Pithoragarh, Uttarakhand, stands an architectural marvel revered for its historical significance - Pithoragarh Fort, also known as London Fort. This fort, which witnessed the rise and fall of empires, offers a glimpse into the bygone eras of Gorkha Raj and the British Raj. Though currently in a dilapidated condition, it remains a testament to the rich heritage that has shaped the region's cultural narrative.

Some historians say it was built by Prithvi Saha/ Raja Pithora.

Pithoragarh Fort traces its roots back to Prithvi Gussain. Overlooking the town, the fort's strategic location offered a vantage point for the army to consolidate their control over the region and establish a stronghold. The fort served as a bastion of power, commanding both respect and fear from those who came across its imposing structure.

Transformation into London Fort

During the British Raj, the fort underwent a transformation and was given the name "London Fort." It is believed that the British administrators, in an effort to assert control and establish a symbolic connection with their colonial empire, renamed the fort. The new name held significance as it mirrored the grandeur and influence of the British capital. This renaming effort reflected the cultural and political dynamics of the time, as the British influence spread its wings across the Indian subcontinent.

Architecture and Present Condition

Pithoragarh Fort showcases a unique blend of architectural styles influenced by the Gorkha and British periods. The fort was originally designed with meticulous detail, featuring sturdy stone walls, watchtowers, and strategic features to repel potential invaders. However, over time the fort continues to stand as a poignant reminder of the region's historical legacy.

Preserving Cultural Heritage

While Pithoragarh Fort currently in good condition, its historical significance continues to resonate with the local community and visitors alike. It serves as a symbol of regional pride and cultural heritage. Efforts to preserve and restore the fort are crucial to ensure that future generations can connect with their roots and understand the rich tapestry of history that has shaped the landscape of Pithoragarh.

Conclusion
Known as London Fort during the British era, is an emblem of the region's historical journey. Constructed during the old times and witness to the trials and tribulations of bygone eras, it holds the potential to transport visitors back in time. Its legacy lives on, reminding us of the need to value and conserve our cultural heritage. A visit to Pithoragarh Fort offers not only a glimpse into the past but also an appreciation for the resilience and rich history that continue to shape the vibrant town of Pithoragarh.

Entry fee required.

Though currently in a dilapidated condition, it remains a testament to the rich heritage that has shaped the region's cultural narrative.

Some historians say it was built by Prithvi Saha/ Raja Pithora.

Pithoragarh Fort traces its roots back to Prithvi Gussain. Overlooking the town, the fort's strategic location offered a vantage point for the army to consolidate their control over the region and establish a stronghold. The fort served as a bastion of power, commanding both respect and fear from those who came across its imposing structure.

Transformation into London Fort

During the British Raj, the fort underwent a transformation and was given the name "London Fort." It is believed that the British administrators, in an effort to assert control and establish a symbolic connection with their colonial empire, renamed the fort. The new name held significance as it mirrored the grandeur and influence of the British capital. This renaming effort reflected the cultural and political dynamics of the time, as the British influence spread its wings across the Indian subcontinent.

Architecture and Present Condition

Pithoragarh Fort showcases a unique blend of architectural styles influenced by the Gorkha and British periods. The fort was originally designed with meticulous detail, featuring sturdy stone walls, watchtowers, and strategic features to repel potential invaders. However, over time the fort continues to stand as a poignant reminder of the region's historical legacy.

Preserving Cultural Heritage

While Pithoragarh Fort currently in good condition, its historical significance continues to resonate with the local community and visitors alike. It serves as a symbol of regional pride and cultural heritage. Efforts to preserve and restore the fort are crucial to ensure that future generations can connect with their roots and understand the rich tapestry of history that has shaped the landscape of Pithoragarh.

Conclusion
Known as London Fort during the British era, is an emblem of the region's historical journey. Constructed during the old times and witness to the trials and tribulations of bygone eras, it holds the potential to transport visitors back in time. Its legacy lives on, reminding us of the need to value and conserve our cultural heritage. A visit to Pithoragarh Fort offers not only a glimpse into the past but also an appreciation for the resilience and rich history that continue to shape the vibrant town of Pithoragarh.

featured_reviews.review_id:
Pithoragarh, a charming town ensconced in the heart of the Himalayas, is not only known for its spiritual sanctuaries but also for its breathtaking landscapes and hiking trails. Among these, the Dhwaj Temple stands as a unique blend of spiritual tranquility and natural beauty. In this article, we will explore the Dhwaj Temple and the enchanting hiking trails that surround it, offering visitors a truly exceptional experience that combines spirituality, adventure, and a deep connection with nature.

The Serenity of Dhwaj Temple

The Dhwaj Temple, located in Pithoragarh, is a significant spiritual destination for locals and pilgrims alike. This temple is dedicated to Lord Shiva and Maa Jayanti and is known for its serene atmosphere, making it an ideal place for meditation and introspection. Devotees and visitors come here to seek solace and spiritual enlightenment while surrounded by the stunning Himalayan landscape.

Hiking Trails in the Vicinity

What makes the Dhwaj Temple even more enticing is its proximity to an array of hiking trails. These trails offer adventure seekers and nature enthusiasts an opportunity to explore the beauty of the Himalayas. As you ascend through the trails, you'll be greeted by lush greenery, pristine streams, and panoramic vistas of the snow-capped peaks. These trails vary in difficulty, catering to both beginners and experienced hikers.

A Glimpse of Nature's Bounty

For nature lovers, the Dhwaj Temple is not only a place of worship but a gateway to the great outdoors. The surrounding trails offer an immersive experience in the lap of nature. You may encounter vibrant flora and fauna, including various species of birds and perhaps even glimpses of Himalayan wildlife. The sensation of crisp mountain air and the soothing sound of gushing streams provide an unparalleled sense of tranquility.

Conclusion

The Dhwaj Temple in Pithoragarh is a testament to the harmonious coexistence of spirituality and adventure. Visitors are drawn not only to the temple's spiritual ambience but also to the enchanting hiking trails that crisscross the Himalayan landscape. The Dhwaj Temple and its surrounding natural wonders offer a perfect fusion of serenity, adventure, and communion with nature. This sacred site is an embodiment of the spiritual and natural riches that Pithoragarh has to offer, making it an unmissable destination for those seeking a holistic experience.

featured_reviews.review_translated_text: Pithoragarh is a beautiful hill station. Where there is the Himalayan mountain range towards the north. In the eastern border, Mahakali river separates it from Nepal. The main rivers flowing here are Mahakali, Saryu, Ramganga, Dhauliganga, Goriganga etc. Dependent on roads for transportation. Naini Saini Airport is also ready here. This hill station, which has immense potential in the field of tourism, is currently the first choice of tourists fond of mountaineering, rock climbing, paragliding, river rafting. Along with this, national and international level football competitions, cricket, boxing, martial arts, badminton, volleyball etc. games are played here in abundance.
